	"Henry..." a woman's voice called. It was clear at first then it faded off into echoes. "I'm here Henry," it called again. It was the same voice he'd heard when he was first in the catacombs, raspy but still fetching; its beauty making it all the more terrifying. The voice was trying to lure him deeper into the tunnel. He wanted to run, to turn around and sprint back towards the entrance as fast as he could, but he forced his fear to the back of his mind. He reminded himself that he had a job to do, and he couldn't go home until the beast was dead. He kept walking, past two more burial chambers.\
	"Henry, come to me," it cried. "I'm waiting..." The voice faded out again. It was almost as if it could control the echos, stretching its calls out into nothing. Henry had no way to tell how far down the voice came from or how far he had walked, but he thought he could see a faint glow up ahead a few hundred feet.\
	"Henry..."\
	"What do you want!" he yelled back as loud as he could, working his fear into a defiant shout. The cry cut through the terror. It was enough to let him continue on towards the glow. As he got closer, he recognized the light. It was a glowstone, very faint after the years, but still going.\
	The tunnel opened up into a circular room like the first one, but nearly twice as large. On a platform in the middle, the glowstone was set into the ring of a very large skeleton. He could hardly believe it was still glowing after centuries underground. The magician who made it must have been extremely powerful. \
	He stepped closer to the opening. Other skeletons lay in alcoves like in the first room. Even the ones who were shackled wore ornate jewelry. The treasure on display here made the previous crypt look like a pauper's grave. Diamonds and rubies glittered on the fingers of long dead nobles, reflecting the light of his lantern back at him. A massive gold crown rested on the head of the central skeleton. Enough wealth to tempt even a saint, but he knew that it was off limits; even if he did kill the Baen Sidhe, the crown would claim the treasure and might notice if anything was missing. \
	Henry entered the room. He heard a rustling sound, and shined his lantern down an opening in the right side of the room. His blood froze. A shadowy figure ran down the tunnel, fleeing the light. He could barely make out an outline, but it was his first glimpse of the Baen Sidhe. 
\f1\i How deep do these tunnels go
\f0\i0 ? he wondered.\
	"I don't have all day," he called out. She could keep leading him deeper and deeper forever, but maybe he could make her come to him. He sat his lantern on the platform in the middle of the room and pulled out the comb. He was probably doing something very stupid, but he had to end this chase. "Do you want this back?" he yelled, holding up the comb in one hand and his gun in the other.\
	A moan rang out from the darkness, a piercing wail that filled Henry with dread. He had its attention, so he steeled himself and cried out, "better come and get it." Then he tossed the comb on the ground. The creature wailed again\'97louder, closer. The voice almost broke his resolve. His heart pounded like a hammer in his chest. It took everything he had not to lie down and curl up in a ball. 	The moan stopped, and then started up again from the opposite direction. He cocked his gun and turned around to face it. The voice grew louder until it seemed to shut down his senses. It was behind him. Before he could turn around, something slammed into him, lifting him off his feet. When he crashed into the ground, he saw a blinding flash, and his mind went blank. He struggled to reorient himself, but he couldn't stand. He lay there, dazed, tasting blood. He touched his hand to his face\'97a flash of pain from a huge gash on his cheek snapped him back to his senses. \
	His lantern was out, and his eyes hadn't adjusted to the dim glowstone. He fumbled for one of the emergency flares in his jacket pocket and struck it. As it burst into flame, his eyes shot to the center of the room, his stomach lurched forward, and his heart slammed into the front of his chest. There it was\'97the Baen Sidhe\'97suddenly thrown into view by the flare. All his carefully repressed fear came screaming to the front of his mind. She was reaching over to pick up her comb, bathed in the devilish red glow of the flare. She was absolutely dreadful. Her long gown was torn to tatters, and her skin was stretched so tight that the bones threatened to break through. Her hair was wild and flailed about even though the air was still. Her fingernails were so long she almost couldn't grasp the comb as she stood there staring at it. There was no trace of beauty left in this horrible creature.\
	Henry reached over and grabbed his gun. The Baen Sidhe snapped her head towards him and met his gaze. Her eyes glowed like fiery coals, illuminating the black depths of the sockets. Her stare cut into his soul; there was nothing there but unquestionable madness. Henry forced himself to focus. Raising the gun to his shoulder, he took aim. "You don't even know enough to be scared," he said in a low growl. How could she? She'd been locked down here long before guns were invented. As she crouched low, he could see her muscles twitch, ready to pounce; she wanted to rip him apart. He pulled the trigger. The hammer slammed down igniting the priming powder. The main charge exploded, hurling the shot towards the creature. In a split second a handful of rock salt buried itself deep in her chest.\
	Henry was hit by a solid wall of sound as the Baen Sidhe shrieked in pain. He threw down his gun and covered his ears. She writhed and clawed at her chest, ripping and tearing the flesh to get at the irritant. It seemed that a Baen Sidhe greatly disliked having salt lodged in its skin.\
	He wasn't sure how long it would take her to recover, so he had to act fast. He fought through the pain in his ears, drew his sword, and walked toward the creature. Suddenly there was a flash\'97where there had been a hideous beast, his wife now lay. He stumbled, dizzy and unsure of what was happening.\
	"Henry, what are you doing? Put down the sword," she pleaded. He looked around. He saw that he was back in his house, and his wife was lying down on their bed. 
\f1\i What's going on?
\f0\i0  Henry wondered. Was this really his wife? Was this a dream, or had he just woken from one? Her eyes were the same dark shade of green he remembered. Her hair was pinned back with her favorite comb. He could even smell her perfume. Everything was the way it should be, and he wanted to believe it, but something didn't feel right. He looked down at her and saw a dark crimson stain spread out on her dress.\
	"What...happened to you?" he asked, distraught.\
	"You shot me, dear," said his wife's soft voice.\
	"I would never do that!" he said, shocked but unsure of himself as the image of muzzle flash still danced in his head. \
	"It doesn't matter, I'll be fine," she assured him. "Now put down the sword and come over here." Why had he shot his wife? And why couldn't he remember what he was just doing? He knew it was something important.\
	"Put down the sword," she said more forcefully. He looked down at his sword, about to throw it aside, but it flashed and caught his eye. He looked down into the improvised mirror, and he could barely make out a reflection. He changed the angle until it was clearer. It was his wife's reflection, but it didn't match. He looked harder, but all he could see was a pale gaunt face where his wife's should have been\'97the Baen Sidhe. Suddenly, it all came back to him. His wife had been gone for fifteen years. This was all a desperate trick. He walked over to the bed, still holding the sword.\
	"Dear, what's wrong?" the Baen Sidhe asked. \
	"Nothing, darling," he said, raising the sword. He looked at the beast impersonating his wife, his heart filled with contempt. "I won't let you tarnish her memory!" he yelled as he prepared to end its cursed existence.\
	The blade swept down in a blur\'97the sharp edge cut through flesh and bone, killing her scream before it could form. The creature's head rolled from its body.\
	Henry grabbed his lantern from the ground and slumped down against a wall, exhausted. As he relit the lamp, flashes of shimmering treasure drew his eyes; the accumulated fortune of an entire noble house, enough gold and jewels to tempt even a saint. A half smile spread to his lips. "Maybe they won't miss just one jewel."\
